-- в”Ђв”Ђ MISP в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$MISP is a free, open-source threat intelligence platform for collecting, storing, correlating, and sharing cybersecurity indicators of compromise and threat information between organizations.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2011, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Luxembourg$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$MISP Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$MISP review: a free, open-source threat intelligence platform for sharing indicators of compromise between security teams. Features, pricing, alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$MISP (originally short for Malware Information Sharing Platform, now generally referred to simply as MISP - Open Source Threat Intelligence Platform) is a free, open-source software project for collecting, storing, correlating, and sharing cybersecurity threat indicators and threat intelligence between organizations and communities. The project began around May 2011 when developer Christophe Vandeplas, frustrated that indicators of compromise (IOCs) were commonly shared informally via email or unstructured PDF documents rather than in machine-parsable formats, started building a proof of concept using the Django-adjacent PHP framework CakePHP. Development and maintenance today are led primarily by CIRCL (the Computer Incident Response Center Luxembourg), the national CERT/CSIRT of Luxembourg, working alongside contributors from Belgian Defence, NATO's NCIRC (Computer Incident Response Capability), and a broad international open-source community. The project has received funding support from the European Union, including through the Connecting Europe Facility program, as well as from CIRCL itself. MISP is released as free and open-source software under the GNU Affero General Public License (AGPL), meaning organizations can self-host their own instance, inspect and modify the source code, and are not required to pay any license fee. Architecturally, MISP functions as a central repository and correlation engine for threat data: security teams ingest indicators (IP addresses, file hashes, domains, malware samples, vulnerability data, and more) as structured events and attributes, and the platform automatically correlates related indicators across events, supports tagging via taxonomies, and enables both automated and manual sharing of intelligence with trusted partner organizations or sharing communities through MISP's peer-to-peer synchronization protocol. Core features include a flexible data model for threat events and attributes, built-in correlation and enrichment, support for open standards like STIX for interoperability with other threat intelligence tools, a REST API and PyMISP Python library for automation and integration with SIEMs and other security tooling, community/organization-based access controls and distribution levels for controlling who can see shared intelligence, and curated MISP feeds and communities that let organizations subscribe to external threat data. Because it is free and open source, there is no official vendor-set pricing tier; costs are limited to self-hosting infrastructure, though the ecosystem includes many free public and vetted MISP communities as well as commercial vendors offering managed MISP hosting or support. MISP's primary audience is security operations centers (SOCs), CERTs/CSIRTs, government cybersecurity agencies, financial sector ISACs, and enterprise threat intelligence teams that need to share and correlate indicators of compromise at scale. Its main competitors and alternatives include commercial and open-source threat intelligence platforms such as OpenCTI, Anomali, ThreatConnect, and Recorded Future, with MISP differentiating itself through its fully free, open-source, community-governed nature and its wide adoption as a de facto standard for structured threat intelligence sharing among government and defense-affiliated CERTs.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'b56d7d7d-6b4d-47bb-b82f-c7a9036e4a72';

